\description{
Compare every level of a treatment factor against one chosen \strong{reference}
(control) level, returning a tidy, means-centric table: the predicted mean of
each level, the reference mean, their difference, and a multiplicity-adjusted
p-value for the difference. This is the honest representation of the common
"how does each treatment compare to the control?" question (a Dunnett-style
analysis), where significance attaches cleanly to each treatment because every
comparison shares the same reference.
}
\details{
Unlike \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}} (all pairs, means + letters) and
\code{\link[=pairwise_comparisons]{pairwise_comparisons()}} (selected differences), \code{reference_comparisons()}
compares each level to a single control and presents the result around the
means. It works for every model supported by \code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}.
\subsection{Why Dunnett is the default}{

Comparing several treatments to one control has an \emph{exact} simultaneous
procedure — Dunnett's test — which uses the joint multivariate-t distribution
of the comparisons (accounting for the correlation induced by the shared
control). It is more powerful than applying a generic adjustment, so it is the
default. The exact test requires a single (common) degrees-of-freedom; for
models that report comparison-specific df, \code{reference_comparisons()} falls
back to \code{"holm"} with a warning. Any \link[stats:p.adjust.methods]{stats::p.adjust.methods} method may be
requested explicitly (a message notes that Dunnett is the exact option).

The multivariate-t routine (\code{\link[mvtnorm:pmvt]{mvtnorm::pmvt()}}) requires an integer
degrees-of-freedom, so a \emph{fractional} denominator df (such as an ASReml-R
Kenward-Roger \code{denDF}) is rounded to the nearest integer for the Dunnett
calculation when two or more comparisons are made. The reported \code{df} column is
the exact (unrounded) value, and a single comparison uses the exact df. In
practice this rounding only affects \code{asreml} models with a fractional denDF
(\code{aov}/\code{lm}/\code{lme} have integer df, and mixed models with comparison-specific df
fall back to Holm).

The Dunnett correlation structure is reconstructed from the standard errors of
the means and the standard errors of differences that the prediction machinery
already returns, so the exact test is available for every supported model
engine. With \code{adjust = "dunnett"} the confidence intervals are the
\emph{simultaneous} Dunnett intervals and therefore agree with the adjusted test
(an interval excludes zero exactly when the comparison is significant). With a
\code{\link[stats:p.adjust]{stats::p.adjust()}} method the intervals are per-comparison and may disagree
with the adjusted p-value.
}

\subsection{\code{by} semantics}{

\code{by} must be a subset of the \code{classify} factors. Within each group, the
reference and the compared levels reference the remaining (non-\code{by}) factor.
For example \code{classify = "Trt:Site"}, \code{by = "Site"}, \code{reference = "Control"}
compares every Trt level against Control \emph{within each Site}, adjusted within
each Site. A group missing the reference, or with fewer than two levels, is
skipped with a warning.

To compare a control level against the others within every combination of the
\emph{remaining} factors, put all the other factors in \code{by}. The within-group
factor is then the single control factor, so \code{reference} is just that level
(e.g. \code{"0"}). For example, with \code{classify = "time:variety:dose"} and a zero
dose labelled \code{"0"}, \code{by = c("time", "variety")}, \code{reference = "0"} compares
each dose against the zero dose within every time-by-variety cell. Specified
this way \code{reference} is a single level, so it is unaffected by the order of
the factors in \code{classify} or \code{by} (those orderings only change the column
order and group labels of the output, not the comparisons).

Without \code{by}, by contrast, \code{reference} is the full \code{:}-joined cell label and
its components must follow the \code{classify} order. A mis-ordered label that
happens to name another valid cell is used silently (no error), so it is
worth double-checking the order matches; the order-proof \code{by} form above
avoids this entirely.
}

\subsection{Transformations}{

Comparisons are reported on the model scale (a difference of transformed means
does not back-transform to a difference on the original scale); a warning is
issued if the response appears to be transformed in the model formula.
}
}
\section{Supported model types}{

The comparison functions (\code{\link[=multiple_comparisons]{multiple_comparisons()}}, \code{\link[=pairwise_comparisons]{pairwise_comparisons()}}
and \code{\link[=reference_comparisons]{reference_comparisons()}}) work with any model for which a
\code{get_predictions()} method is defined. These are currently:\tabular{lll}{
   Model class \tab Fitted by \tab Notes \cr
   \code{aov}, \code{lm} \tab \code{\link[stats:aov]{stats::aov()}}, \code{\link[stats:lm]{stats::lm()}} \tab Fixed-effects linear models. \cr
   \code{aovlist} \tab \code{\link[stats:aov]{stats::aov()}} with an \code{Error()} term \tab Multi-stratum aov; gives comparison-specific (matrix) degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{lme} \tab \code{\link[nlme:lme]{nlme::lme()}} \tab Linear mixed model. \cr
   \code{lmerMod} \tab \code{\link[lme4:lmer]{lme4::lmer()}} \tab Linear mixed model. \cr
   \code{lmerModLmerTest} \tab \code{\link[lmerTest:lmer]{lmerTest::lmer()}} \tab As \code{lmerMod}, with Satterthwaite degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{asreml} \tab ASReml-R \code{asreml()} \tab Linear mixed model (commercial; not on CRAN). \cr
   \code{afex_aov} \tab afex \code{aov_car()} / \code{aov_ez()} / \code{aov_4()} \tab Factorial / repeated-measures ANOVA; gives comparison-specific (matrix) degrees of freedom. \cr
   \code{glmmTMB} \tab glmmTMB \code{glmmTMB()} \tab Generalized linear mixed model. Predictions are on the link scale with asymptotic (infinite) degrees of freedom; supply \code{trans} to back-transform. \cr
   \code{mmes} \tab sommer \code{mmes()} \tab Linear mixed model, via sommer's native \code{predict()}. SED from the prediction covariance; asymptotic (infinite) degrees of freedom (sommer provides none). \cr
}


ARTool (\code{art}) models are supported by \code{\link[=resplot]{resplot()}} but \strong{not} by the comparison
functions: the aligned rank transform makes mean-based comparisons inappropriate.
Use \code{ARTool::art.con()} for contrasts on ART models instead.

sommer \code{mmer} models (the legacy interface) are supported by \code{\link[=resplot]{resplot()}} but
\strong{not} by the comparison functions: current sommer provides no \code{predict()} method
for \code{mmer}. Refit with \code{sommer::mmes()} to use the comparison functions.

To add a new engine, write a \verb{get_predictions.<class>()} method returning a
list with elements \code{predictions}, \code{sed}, \code{df}, \code{ylab} and \code{aliased_names}
(plus \code{emmeans_grid} for engines backed by \code{\link[emmeans:emmeans]{emmeans::emmeans()}}), and add a
row to the table above.
}

\examples{

# Means plot of each level vs the reference (significant ones marked with *)
dat.aov <- aov(Petal.Width ~ Species, data = iris)
rc <- reference_comparisons(dat.aov, classify = "Species", reference = "setosa")
autoplot(rc)
dat.aov <- aov(weight ~ feed, data = chickwts)

# Compare every feed against the "casein" control (exact Dunnett)
reference_comparisons(dat.aov, classify = "feed", reference = "casein")

# A different adjustment can be requested (a message notes that Dunnett is the
# exact option for this family):
reference_comparisons(
    dat.aov,
    classify = "feed",
    reference = "casein",
    adjust = "holm"
)

# `by`: compare each level against the reference *within* each group, adjusted
# independently. Here a 2 x 3 factorial - each tension level vs the "L"
# reference within each wool type; autoplot() facets by wool.
m_wb <- aov(breaks ~ wool * tension, data = warpbreaks)
rc_by <- reference_comparisons(
    m_wb,
    classify = "wool:tension",
    reference = "L",
    by = "wool"
)
rc_by
autoplot(rc_by)
}
